    <h1>Merchant services explained</h1>
    <p>
      Merchant services is the set of tools and agreements that allow a business to accept card payments and receive funds.
      A typical setup involves a processor, an acquiring bank, card networks, and a merchant account configuration.
    </p>

    <h2>Key parties in card processing</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Card networks:</strong> publish interchange tables and set network rules</li>
      <li><strong>Issuing bank:</strong> the customer’s bank</li>
      <li><strong>Acquiring bank:</strong> sponsors card acceptance for the merchant</li>
      <li><strong>Processor:</strong> routes transactions and manages settlement/reporting</li>
      <li><strong>Merchant:</strong> the business accepting the card</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How fees are commonly structured</h2>
    <p>
      Most pricing structures include (1) card network and issuer costs (interchange) and (2) a processor or ISO markup.
      The exact presentation depends on the pricing model and the merchant’s transaction profile.
    </p>

    <h2>How funds move</h2>
    <p>
      After authorization and capture, transactions settle through the processor and acquiring bank, and funds are deposited into the merchant’s bank account
      according to the funding schedule.
    </p>

